      "factorType": "Discretization error",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Grid convergence index (GCI) for primary QoI (NIH) must be below 10% at the design operating point.",
      "rationale": "Three-level mesh refinement study conducted per Celik et al. (2008). GCI for NIH at 5 L/min, 2500 RPM design point computed as 3.7%, well below 10% threshold. Monotonic convergence confirmed with Richardson extrapolation applied. Medium mesh (5.8M cells) selected for production runs."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Test conditions",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Experimental boundary conditions (flow rate, rotational speed, fluid properties) must be replicated in CFD simulations within ±5% of measured values.",
      "rationale": "FDA benchmark experimental conditions (Hariharan et al. 2011) replicated in CFD: flow rates 2.5–7.5 L/min, rotational speeds 2000–3500 RPM, bovine blood analog (glycerol-saline, viscosity 3.5 cP). All boundary conditions matched within ±2% of published experimental values."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Output comparison",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "CFD-predicted NIH values must agree with experimental measurements within ±15% across all 5 operating points.",
      "rationale": "NIH predictions compared against FDA benchmark experimental data at all 5 flow-speed combinations. Mean relative error 8.3%, maximum 14.1%. All predictions within ±15% acceptance band. Systematic under-prediction at high shear conditions (>3000 RPM) noted and attributed to power-law hemolysis model limitations; within acceptance tolerance for MRL 2."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Relevance of the quantities of interest",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Quantities of interest (NIH, RH) must be directly traceable to the clinical endpoint (hemolysis) and the regulatory acceptance criterion (RH < 1).",
      "rationale": "Primary QoI is normalized index of hemolysis (NIH) derived from Lagrangian particle tracking and Giersiepen-Wurzinger power-law model. NIH directly mapped to relative hemolysis index RH via predicate device normalization. RH < 1 criterion directly supports the regulatory decision. QoI relevance confirmed by clinical literature and FDA guidance."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Relevance of the validation activities to the COU",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Validation activities must use a geometrically and operationally similar pump under flow conditions spanning the COU operating envelope.",
      "rationale": "Validation performed on FDA generic centrifugal pump geometry — same geometry used in COU. Operating conditions (2.5–7.5 L/min, 2000–3500 RPM) bracket the CPB clinical operating envelope (4–6 L/min, 2200–3200 RPM). Fluid properties matched to blood analog. Validation relevance to COU is high; gap analysis confirms no extrapolation outside validated parameter space."
    },
    {
